            <h1>Welfare at work</h1>
            <section data-aos="fade" data-aos-duration="1000">
                <h2>What is it?</h2>
                <p>First, the notion of welfare at work is a concept including the notions of physical and
                    mental health but not exclusively. It refers to a feeling of satisfaction and
                    fulfillment at work. Welfare refers to the personal and collective perception of
                    situations and constraints in the personal sphere. Consequently, welfare at work is
                    specific to everyone and translates into a certain level of efficiency for the company.
                </p>
            </section>
            <section data-aos="fade" data-aos-duration="1000">
                <h2>What influences welfare at work?</h2>
                <p>First, there are the so-called "material" problems which mainly concern the working
                    environment, and therefore the comfort of the workstation, the brightness, the technical
                    conditions, and the safety of the employees. But there are also "psychosocial" problems,
                    such as stress (65% of workers (1)) but also burnout and bore-out, poor job recognition,
                    moral harassment (31% of workers (2)) but also and mainly the imbalance between private
                    and professional life. Finally, the sense of mission is also a key element since
                    employees are more fulfilled in their work if they have the feeling of contributing to
                    the success of the company and meeting specific needs.</p>
            </section>
            <section data-aos="fade" data-aos-duration="1000">
                <h2>How to improve the well-being of its employees?</h2>
                <p>For a company, the simplest thing to do is to work on the collective welfare. For this
                    purpose, it is possible to set up various projects to contribute to the improvement of
                    the physical and mental health of the employees. For example, greening workspaces (20%
                    of people want it (3 and 4)) increases creativity, welfare, and productivity by 15% for
                    people sensitive to this project. It is also interesting to set up various common rooms
                    such as nap rooms, sports halls, and a decent cafeteria. (4, 5 and 6). Although very
                    popular in recent years, open spaces increase the stress of employees for about 45% of
                    them (7 and 8). In a world where we care a little more about the environment and
                    sustainable development every day, it is also beneficial to set up eco projects.</p>
            </section>
            <section data-aos="fade" data-aos-duration="1000">
                <h2>Why worry about the well-being of its employees?</h2>
                <p>First, when an employee is happy to work, he will be 12 to 13% more productive (9) but
                    also, if the employer cares about the well-being of his employees in the company then
                    this will contribute to the improvement of the attractiveness of his company and
                    therefore he will be able to seduce and attract better profiles (10).On the opposite,
                    poor working conditions cause an increase in absenteeism as well as resignations (10)
                </p>
            </section>
